# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angela-merkel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 14 August 1949 to elect the members of the first Bundestag, with a further eight seats elected in West Berlin between 1949 and January 1952 and another eleven between February 1952 and 1953.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] They were the first free federal elections in West Germany since 1933 and the first after the division of the country.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU formed a centre-right coalition government with the FDP and the DP.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] Most West German parties at the time of the 1949 Bundestag election were committed to democracy, but they disagreed on what kind of democracy West Germany should become.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic (CDU) leader, 73-year-old Konrad Adenauer, former mayor of Cologne and party chairman in the British Zone since March 1946, believed in moderate, non-denominational and Christian democracy, social market economy and integration with the West.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] In 1948 he had become president of the *Parlamentarischer Rat*, an office that added to his popularity as protagonist of a "state-to-be".
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] He attacked social democracy and the British, especially, dismantling of industry.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic (SPD) leader, Kurt Schumacher, wanted a united, democratic and socialist Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] He constantly accused Adenauer of betraying national interests, culminating in his heckling at the Bundestag session of 25 September 1949: "The Chancellor of the Allies!".
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] Schumacher criticized the Catholic Church, calling it the fifth occupying power and criticized denominational education.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] In the end and to the great disappointment of the Social Democrats, the CDU/CSU outnumbered them by 31.0% to 29.2% of the votes cast.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] To enter the Bundestag, a party had to surmount a threshold of 5% at least in one of the states or to win at least one electoral district; ten parties succeeded.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] A number of non-voting members (elected in 1949:2 CDU, 5 SPD, 1 FDP; joined in February 1952 by: 3 CDU, 4 SPD, 4 FDP) indirectly elected by the West Berlin legislature (*Stadtverordnetenversammlung*) are included below in parentheses.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] The French Saar Protectorate did not participate in this election.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] 41 of the members elected to the Bundestag were refugees.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] Schumacher had explicitly refused a grand coalition and led his party into opposition, where it would remain until December 1966, assuming the chair of the SPD parliamentary group as minority leader.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] On 12 September 1949, he lost the indirect German presidential election, defeated by FDP chairman Theodor Heuss in the second ballot.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] Schumacher died on 20 August 1952 of the long-term consequences of his concentration camp imprisonment during the Nazi years.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] Adenauer had favoured the formation of a smaller centre-right coalition from the beginning.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] Nominated by the CDU/CSU faction, he was elected the first Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany on 15 September 1949 by an absolute majority of 202 of 402 votes.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] Adenauer had ensured that the votes of the predominantly Social Democrat West Berlin deputies did not count and later stated that he "naturally" had voted for himself.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] On 20 September, he formed the Cabinet Adenauer I of CDU/CSU, FDP, and DP ministers.
[src:angela-merkel/1949-west-german-federal-election] Chosen as an interim Chancellor, he held the office until 1963, being re-elected three times (in 1953, in 1957 and in 1961).
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 6 September 1953 to elect the members of the second Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU) emerged as the largest party.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] This was the last election before Saarland joined West Germany in 1957.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] It had been a separate entity, Saar protectorate, under French control since 1946.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU formed a center-right coalition government with the FDP, DP and GB/BHE, leaving the SPD as the main opposition.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] In comparison to the 1949 election where ten parties won seats, only six parties won seats in the 1953 election, thus entailing a consolidation of the party system.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] Federal Chancellor Konrad Adenauer (who was also CDU leader) campaigned on his policies of economic reconstruction and growth, moderate conservatism or Christian democracy, and close relations with the United States.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] During the campaign he attacked the Social Democratic Party (SPD) ferociously.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] His staff had a comfortable coach on a train previously used only by Hermann Göring and behind that a dining car with sleeping berths for journalists.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] The new SPD leader (Kurt Schumacher had died in 1952) was Erich Ollenhauer, who was more moderate in his policies than Schumacher had been.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] He did not oppose, in principle, the United States' military presence in Western Europe.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] He later – in 1957 – supported a military alliance of most European countries, including Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/1953-west-german-federal-election] Konrad Adenauer remained Chancellor, governing in a broad coalition (two-thirds majority) with most of the minor parties except for the SPD and Centre Party.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 15 September 1957 to elect the members of the third Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union and its longtime ally, the Christian Social Union in Bavaria, won a sweeping victory, taking 270 seats in the Bundestag to win the first–and, to date, only–absolute majority for a single German parliamentary group in a free election.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] This was the first West German federal election to take place in the Saarland, which–as Saar protectorate–had been a separate entity under French control between 1946 and 1956.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] Only four parties won seats in the 1957 election, which was a consolidation of the party system relative to the 1953 and 1949 elections where six and ten parties won seats respectively.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] As the CDU/CSU won a majority of seats, it formed a government without coalition partners.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] West Germany had joined the European Economic Community in March 1957.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] Its economy was growing steadily with very low unemployment, and most West Germans felt more prosperous and more secure than in 1949 or 1953.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] Adenauer at first tried to brush the matter aside, but under heavy criticism from the press decided instead to meet with five of the physicists in Bonn.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] Ultimately the row was too far away from the election itself to damage a surprisingly healthy looking Adenauer's prospects.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] The All-German Bloc lost all of their seats, but the ideologically similar German Party maintained theirs.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] The 1957 election was the last time that a right-wing populist party would return members to the Bundestag until Alternative for Germany's entrance in 2017.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] The election also marked the last time until 1990 that any party other than CDU/CSU or SPD won any constituency seats.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] Konrad Adenauer led the CDU-CSU coalition to a landslide victory.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] The CDU-CSU won an outright majority— the only to date.
[src:angela-merkel/1957-west-german-federal-election] Since the CDU and the CSU form a single bloc in the Bundestag, this is the only time that a political party in Germany has been elected to a majority government in a free election.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 17 September 1961 to elect the members of the fourth Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU remained the largest faction, winning 242 of the 499 seats.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] The election campaign occurred in the context of the Berlin Crisis and the erection of the Berlin Wall.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] For the first time, the SPD announced a Chancellor candidate who was not chairman of the party: Willy Brandt, the Governing Mayor of West Berlin.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] After the building of the Berlin Wall, he gained more and more sympathy, while chancellor Konrad Adenauer was criticised for not showing enough support for the people of West Berlin.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] Adenauer had to save the absolute majority of CDU and CSU, but, considering his age and his long term as chancellor, there were big doubts if he should lead the country in a fourth term.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] The absolute majority was lost by the conservative union due to the gains of the liberal FDP under Erich Mende.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] From 1961 on, the Union, SPD and FDP established an electoral "triopoly" in the Bundestag that would last until 1983.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] Konrad Adenauer remained Chancellor, building a coalition between the CDU/CSU-FDP.
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] In 1962 he had to announce a fifth cabinet: The FDP had temporarily left the coalition after the secretary of defense, Franz Josef Strauß (CSU), had ordered the arrest of five journalists for publishing a memo detailing alleged weaknesses in the German armed forces (known as the Spiegel scandal).
[src:angela-merkel/1961-west-german-federal-election] In 1963 Adenauer finally retired; Ludwig Erhard took over his position as head of the coalition government.
[src:angela-merkel/1965-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 19 September 1965 to elect the members of the 5th Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/1965-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU remained the largest faction, while the Social Democratic Party remained the largest single party in the Bundestag, winning 217 of the 518 seats (including 15 of the 22 non-voting delegates for West Berlin).
[src:angela-merkel/1965-west-german-federal-election] Federal Chancellor Ludwig Erhard was initially popular as the acclaimed "father" of West Germany's economic miracle of the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:angela-merkel/1965-west-german-federal-election] West Germany's economy still seemed solid in 1965, and thus not enough West German voters wanted to change the party of Federal Chancellor.
[src:angela-merkel/1965-west-german-federal-election] To ensure his victory in this Bundestag election, Erhard promised to cut income tax and to increase social program spending.
[src:angela-merkel/1965-west-german-federal-election] The coalition between the CDU/CSU and the FDP returned to government, with Ludwig Erhard as Chancellor.
[src:angela-merkel/1965-west-german-federal-election] In 1966, the FDP left the coalition over budget issues, and Erhard resigned.
[src:angela-merkel/1965-west-german-federal-election] Kurt Georg Kiesinger (also CDU) formed a new grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and the SPD which lasted until the next election.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 28 September 1969 to elect the members of the 6th Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU remained the largest faction and the Social Democratic Party (SDP) remained the largest single party in the Bundestag, winning 237 of the 518 seats.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] After the election, the SPD formed a coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP) and the former's leader Willy Brandt became the first Social Democratic Chancellor in West Germany's history, bringing an end to 20 years of CDU/CSU rule.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] After the resignation of Chancellor Ludwig Erhard on 1 December 1966, a grand coalition of Christian Democrats and Social Democrats had governed West Germany under Chancellor Kurt Georg Kiesinger (CDU), with SPD chairman Willy Brandt as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] Minister of Economic Affairs Karl Schiller (SPD) had proposed revaluing (increasing the external value of) the Deutsche Mark, West Germany's currency, to reduce the country's inflation rate and the rate of growth of the country's businesses' income.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] He also sought to reduce West Germany's economic dependence on the exports.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] However, Finance Minister Franz-Josef Strauss (CSU) rejected the Deutsche Mark's revaluation because Bavarian farmers, an important part of his constituency, opposed it.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] The European Economic Community's food commodity prices were paid in U.S. dollars, and the Deutsche Mark's revaluation would have made West German exports less competitive (i.e. more expensive for other Western Europeans to buy).
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] The coalition had already effectively ended before the election because of the revaluation dispute.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] In addition, enough West German voters were willing to give the Social Democratic leader, Foreign Minister Willy Brandt, a chance to govern West Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] Brandt, who ran for the third time after 1961 and 1965, had shown sympathy towards groups, including left-wing intellectuals and activists of the German student movement, who had felt ignored by the Christian Democrat-led coalition governments.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] In addition, his intellect, self-control and reputation for honesty appealed to ordinary West Germans.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] Willy Brandt, against the will of several party fellows like Herbert Wehner or Helmut Schmidt, chose to leave the grand coalition with the CDU/CSU, forming a social-liberal coalition with the Free Democratic Party (FDP) instead.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] On 21 October 1969 he was elected Chancellor of Germany, the first SPD chancellor in the postwar period, after the last Social Democrat holding this position had been Hermann Müller from 1928 to 1930.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] FDP chairman Walter Scheel succeeded Brandt as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] Brandt's government proceeded with the revaluation Schiller had proposed, raising the value of the mark by 9.3% in late October.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] Disappointed Kiesinger bitterly complained about the faithless liberals.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] Though he had again achieved the plurality of votes for the CDU, he had to lead his party into opposition.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] He was succeeded as chairman by Rainer Barzel in 1971.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] However the Cabinet Brandt I could only rely on an absolute majority (*Kanzlermehrheit*) of twelve votes in the Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/1969-west-german-federal-election] Several party switches in protest against Brandt's *Ostpolitik* of FDP and SPD members resulted in the snap election of 1972.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 19 November 1972 to elect the members of the seventh Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] In the first snap elections since the resumption of democratic elections in 1949, the Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest party in parliament, winning 230 of the 496 seats.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] The SPD's Willy Brandt remained chancellor after resuming his coalition government with the Free Democratic Party.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 27 April 1972 the opposition had tried to have CDU leader Rainer Barzel elected new chancellor in a constructive vote of no confidence, but Barzel surprisingly missed the majority of 249 by two votes.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] Rumours that at least one member of the CDU/CSU faction had been paid by the East German *Stasi* to abstain (in effect, voting against Barzel) were confirmed by Markus Wolf, former head of the *Hauptverwaltung Aufklärung*, in 1997.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] Nevertheless, the following budget debates revealed that the government's majority was lost and only the upcoming organisation of the 1972 Summer Olympics in Munich delayed the arrangement of new elections.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 22 September 1972 Chancellor Brandt asked for a vote of confidence, which required the same majority of 249 "yes" votes: it failed with 233 "yes" votes to 246 "no" votes.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] The members of the government did not participate (in effect, voting no) to ensure the vote would fail, however it would have regardless.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] This allowed Brandt to advise President Gustav Heinemann to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections the same day.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] In the tense campaign, the CDU/CSU attacked Brandt as being too lenient towards Eastern Europe and having the wrong ideas on the economy.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] SPD and FDP benefited from the enormous personal popularity of the chancellor, laureate of the 1971 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] He gained the support by numerous celebrities of the West German culture and media scene (e.g.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] Günter Grass), expressed by the slogan *Willy wählen!* ("Vote for Willy!").
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] Voter turnout was 91.1%, the highest ever since 1949.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] In 1970 the voting age had been lowered from 21 to 18.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] The SPD celebrated their best result ever, representing the largest faction in the German parliament for the first time since the 1930 Reichstag elections.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] It enabled the party to nominate Annemarie Renger for President of the Bundestag; she was the first Social Democrat and also the first woman to hold this office.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 14 December 1972 the Bundestag MPs of the social-liberal coalition re-elected Willy Brandt chancellor.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] His Cabinet Brandt II returned to government the next day, again with FDP chairman Walter Scheel as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] Defeated Rainer Barzel resigned as CDU chairman on 9 May 1973; he was succeeded by Helmut Kohl.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 7 May 1974, Brandt would resign in the course of the Guillaume Affair, after one of his personal aides had been unmasked as a *Stasi* agent.
[src:angela-merkel/1972-west-german-federal-election] The coalition continued under his party fellow Helmut Schmidt, while Brandt remained SPD chairman until 1987.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was born in Hamburg in West Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Her family moved to East Germany when she was an infant.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] A member of the communist East German Free German Youth (FDJ), Merkel obtained a doctorate in quantum chemistry in 1986 and worked as a research scientist until 1989.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She then entered politics in the wake of the Revolutions of 1989, briefly serving as deputy spokeswoman for the first democratically elected government of East Germany, led by Lothar de Maizière.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Following German reunification in 1990, Merkel was elected to the Bundestag for the state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] As the protégée of Chancellor Helmut Kohl, Merkel was appointed as Minister for Women and Youth in 1991, later becoming Minister for the Environment, Nature Conservation and Nuclear Safety in 1994.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] After the CDU lost the 1998 federal election, Merkel was elected general secretary of the party.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She then became the party's first female leader, and the first female leader of the Opposition, two years later.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Following the 2005 federal election, Merkel was elected chancellor, leading a grand coalition consisting of the CDU, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She was the first woman to be elected chancellor, and the first chancellor of reunified Germany to have been raised in the former East Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2009 federal election, the CDU obtained the largest share of the vote, and Merkel subsequently formed a coalition government with the Free Democratic Party (FDP), an alliance more favourable to the CDU than the grand coalition.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2013 federal election, the CDU won a landslide victory and formed a second grand coalition with the SPD, after the FDP lost all of its representation in the Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2017 federal election, Merkel led the CDU to become the largest party for the fourth time, resulting in the formation of a third grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In foreign policy, Merkel emphasised international cooperation, both in the context of the EU and NATO, and initiating the Russian reset and strengthening of Eurasian and transatlantic economic relations.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the first half of 2007, Merkel served as president of the European Council and played a central role in the negotiation of the Treaty of Lisbon and the Berlin Declaration.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's governments managed the 2008 financial crisis and the Euro area crisis.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She negotiated the 2008 European Union stimulus plan, which focused on infrastructure spending and public investment to counteract the Great Recession.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Also in 2008, she actively blocked the access of Ukraine and Georgia in the enlargement of NATO during the 2008 Bucharest summit.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In domestic policy, Merkel's *Energiewende* programme supported the development of renewable energy sources and eventually phased out the use of nuclear power in Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Despite the 2014 Russian annexation of Crimea, which prompted sanctions around the world, she initiated the construction of the controversial Nord Stream 2 pipelines to Russia and protected their construction from United States sanctions imposed in 2019.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Reforms to the *Bundeswehr*, health care reform, the 2010s European migrant crisis, and the COVID-19 pandemic were major issues during her chancellorship.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel stepped down as leader of the CDU in 2018 and did not seek a fifth term as chancellor in the 2021 federal election.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, her legacy came under increased scrutiny both in Germany and abroad for her relatively good relations with Russia and increasing the German economy's dependence on Russia, as well as the downsizing of the *Bundeswehr* that occurred during her tenure.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She has two younger siblings, Marcus Kasner, a physicist, and Irene Kasner, an occupational therapist.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In her childhood and youth, Merkel was known among her peers by the nickname "Kasi", derived from her last name Kasner.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Her paternal grandfather, Ludwik Kasner, was a German policeman of Polish ethnicity.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] After being captured in France during World War I, he joined the Blue Army and likely fought against Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] He married Merkel's grandmother Margarethe, a German from Berlin, and relocated to her hometown where he again worked in the police.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 1930, they Germanised the Polish name Kaźmierczak to Kasner.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's maternal grandparents were the Danzig politician Willi Jentzsch and Gertrud Alma (née Drange), a daughter of the city clerk of Elbing (now Elbląg, Poland) Emil Drange.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Since the mid-1990s, Merkel has publicly mentioned her Polish heritage on several occasions and described herself as a quarter Polish, but her Polish roots became better known as a result of a 2013 biography.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Religion played a key role in the Kasner family's migration from West Germany to East Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's paternal grandfather was originally Catholic but the entire family converted to Lutheranism during the childhood of her father, who later studied Lutheran theology in Heidelberg and Hamburg.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 1954, when Angela was just three months old, her father received a pastorate at the church in Quitzow (a district of Perleberg in Brandenburg), which was then in East Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The family moved to Templin and Merkel grew up in the countryside 90 km (56 mi) north of East Berlin.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 1968, Merkel joined the Free German Youth (FDJ), the official communist youth movement sponsored by the ruling Marxist–Leninist Socialist Unity Party of Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Membership was nominally voluntary, but those who did not join found it difficult to gain admission to higher education.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She did not participate in the secular coming-of-age ceremony Jugendweihe, however, which was common in East Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] During this time, she participated in several compulsory courses on Marxism–Leninism, with her grades only being regarded as "sufficient".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She completed her school education with the best possible average Abitur grade of 1.0.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel continued her education at Karl Marx University, Leipzig, where she studied physics from 1973 to 1978.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] While a student, she participated in the reconstruction of the ruin of the Moritzbastei, a project students initiated to create their own club and recreation facility on campus.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Such an initiative was unprecedented in the GDR of that period, and initially resisted by the university.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] With the backing of the local leadership of the SED party, the project was allowed to proceed.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Near the end of her studies, Merkel sought an assistant professorship at an engineering school.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] As a condition for getting the job, Merkel was told she would need to agree to report on her colleagues to officers of the Stasi.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel declined, using the excuse that she could not keep secrets well enough to be an effective spy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel worked and studied at the Central Institute for Physical Chemistry of the Academy of Sciences in Berlin-Adlershof from 1978 to 1990.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] At first, she and her husband squatted in Mitte.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] At the Academy of Sciences, she became a member of its FDJ secretariat.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] According to her former colleagues, she openly propagated Marxism as the secretary for "Agitation and Propaganda".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, Merkel has denied this claim and stated that she was secretary for culture, which involved activities like obtaining theatre tickets and organising talks by visiting Soviet authors.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] After being awarded a doctorate (*Dr. rer. nat.*) for her thesis on quantum chemistry in 1986, she worked as a researcher and published several academic papers.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 1986, she was allowed to travel to West Germany to attend a congress.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She also participated in a multi-week Russian language course in Donetsk, in the then-Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989 served as the catalyst for Merkel's political career.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although she did not participate in the crowd celebrations the night the wall came down, one month later Merkel became involved in the growing democracy movement, joining the new party Democratic Awakening (*Demokratischer Aufbruch*, abbreviated to DA).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Party Leader Wolfgang Schnur appointed her as press spokeswoman of the party in February 1990.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, Schnur was revealed to have served as an "informal co-worker" for the Stasi just a few weeks ahead of the first (and only) multi-party election in 1990 and was later expelled from the party.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] As a result, the DA lost most of its electoral support, only managing to obtain four seats in the Volkskammer.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, because the DA was a member party of the Alliance for Germany, which won the election in a landslide, the DA was included in the government coalition.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was appointed deputy spokesperson of this last pre-unification government under Lothar de Maizière.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] De Maizière was impressed with the way Merkel handled journalists investigating Schnur's role in the Stasi.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In April 1990, the DA merged with the East German Christian Democratic Union, which in turn merged with its western counterpart after reunification.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the German federal election of 1990, the first to be held following reunification, Merkel successfully stood for election to the Bundestag in the parliamentary constituency of Stralsund – Nordvorpommern – Rügen in North Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She received the crucial backing of influential CDU minister and state party chairman Günther Krause.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She was re-elected from this constituency (renamed, with slightly adjusted borders, Vorpommern-Rügen – Vorpommern-Greifswald I in 2003) in every election until the CDU lost its direct mandate from the constituency in the 2021 federal election.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Almost immediately following her entry into parliament, Merkel was appointed by Chancellor Helmut Kohl to serve as Minister for Women and Youth in the federal cabinet.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In November 1991, Merkel, with the support of the federal CDU, ran for the state leadership of the CDU in the state of Brandenburg, which neighbours Berlin.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In June 1993, Merkel was elected leader of the CDU in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, succeeding her former mentor Günther Krause.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although Merkel had little interest in the political position as such, it has been described as instrumental in building her early political image.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] During her tenure, the government codified the right to preschool education, although the law only went into effect in 1996.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In June 1992, § 218 of the StGB, which governed abortion rights, was rewritten to allow abortions until the 12th week of pregnancy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Though she was personally opposed to abortion at the time, Merkel abstained during the vote on the bill.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The law was later overturned by the Federal Constitutional Court on the basis that there must be a general prohibition of abortion.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 1994, she was promoted to the position of Minister for the Environment and Nuclear Safety, which gave her greater political visibility and a platform on which to build her personal political career.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] As one of Kohl's protégées and his youngest Cabinet Minister, she was frequently referred to by Kohl as "my girl" (*mein Mädchen*).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] During this period, she was closely mentored by Kohl.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] As Minister of the Environment, Merkel was instrumental in setting up the United Nations 1995 Berlin Climate Change Conference.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She is often credited as having brought about its most notable result, the first international commitment to a reduction of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Around this time, she also first hired Beate Baumann, who would remain a close advisor to Merkel.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's performance as Minister of the Environment was criticised as "pitiful" by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] After the Kohl Government was defeated at the 1998 election, Merkel was appointed Secretary-General of the CDU.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The 1998 election had widespread impacts; it was the CDU's worst performance in a federal election since 1949, and it resulted in Germany's first post-war left-wing government, led by the SPD.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the wake of this defeat on the federal level, Merkel oversaw a string of CDU election victories in six out of seven state elections in 1999, breaking the long-standing SPD-Green hold on the Bundesrat.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Following a party funding scandal that compromised many leading figures of the CDU – including Kohl himself and his successor as CDU Leader, Wolfgang Schäuble – Merkel criticised her former mentor publicly and advocated a fresh start for the party without him.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 10 April 2000, Merkel was elected to replace Schäuble as Chairperson of the CDU, becoming the first female leader of a German party.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Following Merkel's election as CDU Leader, the CDU did not obtain electoral victories in subsequent state elections.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In February 2001, her rival Friedrich Merz voiced his intention to become Gerhard Schröder's main challenger for Chancellorship in the 2002 election.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's ambition to become Chancellor was well-known, but she lacked the support of the most influential members within her own party.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Rival candidate and leader of the CSU Edmund Stoiber was much more popular within the party at the time.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In a private negotiation that came to be known as the Wolfratshausen Breakfast, Merkel agreed to cede the opportunity to challenge Schröder to Stoiber; in exchange, she was to become leader of the CDU/CSU faction in the Bundestag following the election.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although pre-election polling had indicated that voters strongly favoured Stoiber, he went on to lose the election by a thin margin.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The election campaign was dominated by the Iraq War.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] While Chancellor Schröder had made clear he would not join the war in Iraq, Merkel was in support of the war at the time, although she later claimed that she had opposed it.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] After Stoiber's defeat in 2002, in addition to her role as CDU Leader, Merkel became Leader of the Opposition in the Bundestag, as had been agreed upon between her and Stoiber.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Friedrich Merz, who had held the post prior to the 2002 election, was eased out to make way for Merkel.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel supported a substantial reform agenda for Germany's economic and social system and was considered more pro-market than her own party (the CDU).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She advocated German labour law changes, specifically removing barriers to laying off employees and increasing the allowed number of work hours in a week.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She argued that existing laws made the country less competitive, because companies could not easily control labour costs when business was slow.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel argued that Germany should phase out nuclear power less quickly than the Schröder administration had planned.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel advocated a strong transatlantic partnership and German-American friendship.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the spring of 2003, defying strong public opposition, Merkel came out in favour of the 2003 invasion of Iraq, describing it as "unavoidable".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She also criticised the government's support for the accession of Turkey to the European Union, instead arguing in favour of a "privileged partnership".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 30 May 2005, Merkel won the CDU/CSU nomination to challenge Chancellor Gerhard Schröder of the SPD in the 2005 federal elections.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Her party began the campaign with a 21–point lead over the SPD in national opinion polls, although her personal popularity lagged behind that of the incumbent.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, the CDU/CSU campaign suffered when Merkel, having made economic competence central to the CDU's platform, confused gross and net income twice during a televised debate.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She regained some momentum after she announced that she would appoint Paul Kirchhof, a former judge at the German Constitutional Court and leading fiscal policy expert, as Minister of Finance.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel and the CDU lost ground after Kirchhof proposed the introduction of a flat tax in Germany, again undermining the party's broad appeal on economic affairs.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] This was compounded by Merkel's proposal to increase VAT to reduce Germany's deficit and fill the gap in revenue from a flat tax.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The SPD were able to increase their support simply by pledging not to introduce flat taxes or increase VAT.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although Merkel's standing recovered after she distanced herself from Kirchhof's proposals, she remained considerably less popular than Schröder, who had been perceived as the more generally competent and trustworthy candidate.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The CDU's lead was down to 9 percentage points on the eve of the election, with Merkel having a significant lead in popularity based on opinion polls.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 18 September 2005, Merkel's CDU/CSU and Schröder's SPD went head-to-head in the national elections, with the CDU/CSU winning 35.2% (CDU 27.8% / CSU 7.5%) of the second votes to the SPD's 34.2%.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The result was so close that both Schröder and Merkel initially claimed victory.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Neither the SPD–Green coalition nor the CDU/CSU and its preferred coalition partners, the Free Democratic Party, held enough seats to form a majority in the Bundestag.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] A grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and SPD would face the challenge of both parties demanding the chancellorship.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, after three weeks of negotiations, the two parties reached a deal for a grand coalition whereby Merkel would become Chancellor and the SPD would hold 8 of the 16 seats in the cabinet.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The deal was approved by both parties at party conferences on 14 November 2005.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel was elected Chancellor by the majority of delegates (397 to 217) in the newly assembled Bundestag on 22 November 2005, but 51 members of the governing coalition voted against her.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Reports at the time indicated that the grand coalition would pursue a mix of policies, some of which differed from Merkel's political platform as leader of the opposition and candidate for Chancellor.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The coalition's intent was to cut public spending whilst increasing VAT (from 16 to 19%), social insurance contributions and the top rate of income tax.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] When announcing the coalition agreement, Merkel stated that the main aim of her government would be to reduce unemployment, and that it was this issue on which her government would be judged.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Reform of the German healthcare system was a salient issue during the 2005 election; the previous system had been criticised as inefficient and overly bureaucratic.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] After a significant period of negotiations, a deal was passed in 2006.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] While this agreement was described as having "saved the coalition government", it was also widely criticised as ineffectual.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The deal also increased the tax burden on employers and their publicly insured employees.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The 2006 round of reforms introduced the "health insurance duty", which establishes that individuals must be insured either through the public insurance system or through private insurance firms and accordingly cannot be uninsured.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The reforms also targeted preventive healthcare as a priority, particularly with regards to eldercare.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 4 October 2008, following the Irish Government's decision to guarantee all deposits in private savings accounts, a move she had strongly criticised, Merkel said there were no plans for the German Government to do the same.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The following day, Merkel stated that the government would guarantee private savings account deposits, after all.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, two days later, on 6 October 2008, it emerged that the pledge was simply a political move that would not be backed by legislation.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Most other European governments eventually either raised the limits or promised to guarantee savings in full.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The German government stepped in to assist the mortgage company Hypo Real Estate with a bailout.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The deal was agreed upon on 6 October, with German banks contributing €30 billion and the Bundesbank €20 billion to an emergency credit line.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] At the time of the Greek government-debt crisis, Germany was the largest creditor of the Greek government, giving it significant negotiating power.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel is often credited as having "saved the Euro", primarily due to her coordinating role in the development of debt relief policy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The austerity measures imposed on debtors such as Greece, which were a significant part of Merkel's position in the negotiations, have been criticised as overly harsh by some observers.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Critics also highlighted Germany's own debt management issues.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the course of the 2008 financial crisis, the Merkel cabinet increased the budget of the Kurzarbeit programme significantly and extended the permitted duration of such contracts from 6 months to 18 months.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although similar provisions had existed previously, the Merkel cabinet's expansion of the programme was widely praised and is credited with having saved 500,000 jobs during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's CDU was re-elected in 2009 with an increased number of seats and could form a governing coalition with the FDP.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] After brief negotiations, the second Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 28 October 2009.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In early 2011, Merkel's approval ratings plummeted, resulting in heavy losses in state elections for her party.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] An August 2011 poll found her coalition had only 36% support compared to a rival potential coalition's 51%.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Notwithstanding the effects of the 2008 financial crisis, unemployment sank below 3 million unemployed people in 2011.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Following increased debate on the subject in the summer of 2010, the German government announced plans to abolish conscription in Germany, making the *Bundeswehr* a volunteer military, in November 2010.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The decision was finalised in December that year, and conscription was suspended on 1 July 2011.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although somewhat popular at the time, the decision has later come under scrutiny, particularly following to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] It has also been criticised in conjunction with Germany's financial commitments to NATO.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2023, 61% of Germans said that they were in favour of reestablishing conscription.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Responding to a budget deficit of €11 billion in the public healthcare system in 2009, the Merkel government passed widely unpopular healthcare reforms in 2010.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The changes reduced healthcare spending in certain areas and increased employer and employee contributions to 15.5% of gross wages.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The reforms also established that future contribution increases would only affect the contributions by employers, which was criticised by opposition parties and trade unions.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the election of September 2013, Merkel won one of the most decisive victories in German history, achieving the best result for the CDU/CSU since reunification and coming within five seats of the first absolute majority in the Bundestag since 1957.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, their preferred coalition partner, the FDP, failed to enter parliament for the first time since 1949, being below the minimum of 5% of second votes required to enter parliament.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The CDU/CSU turned to the SPD to form the third grand coalition in postwar German history and the second under Merkel's leadership.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The third Cabinet of Angela Merkel was sworn in on 17 December 2013.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel scored well in opinion polls on her handling of the recent euro crisis (69% rated her performance as good rather than poor), and her approval rating reached an all-time high of 77% in February 2012 and again in July 2014.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Throughout the course of the European migrant crisis, Merkel encouraged cooperation between EU member states, urging that Europe needs to act "as a whole".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In late August 2015, at the height of the crisis, Merkel's government suspended the Dublin Regulation, which stipulated that asylum seekers must seek asylum in the first EU country they arrive in.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel announced that Germany would also process asylum applications from Syrian refugees if they had come to Germany through other EU countries.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] That year, nearly 1.1 million asylum seekers entered Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel coined the phrase *Wir schaffen das* (literally 'We can do this') around this time.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Junior coalition partner and Vice Chancellor Sigmar Gabriel said that Germany could take in 500,000 refugees annually for the next several years.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] German opposition to the government's admission of the new wave of migrants was strong and coupled with a rise in anti-immigration protests.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel insisted that Germany had the economic strength to cope with the influx of migrants and reiterated that there is no legal maximum limit on the number of migrants Germany can take.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2015, enthusiastic crowds across the country welcomed arriving refugees and migrants.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Horst Seehofer, leader of the Christian Social Union in Bavaria (CSU)—the sister party of Merkel's Christian Democratic Union—and then-Bavarian Minister President, attacked Merkel's policies.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] He argued for a punitive reduction in EU funding for member countries that rejected mandatory refugee quotas.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Meanwhile, Yasmin Fahimi, secretary-general of the Social Democratic Party (SPD), the junior partner of the ruling coalition, praised Merkel's policy allowing migrants in Hungary to enter Germany as "a strong signal of humanity to show that Europe's values are valid also in difficult times".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's approval rating dropped to 54% in October 2015, the lowest it had been since 2011.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In November 2015, there were talks inside the governing coalition to stop family unification for migrants for two years and to establish "Transit Zones" on the border.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Additionally, there were plans to provide housing to migrants with a low likelihood of getting approved for asylum until the processing of their application.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] This led to increased tensions between the CSU, who were generally in favour of these measures and threatened to leave the coalition without them, and the SPD, who opposed them; Merkel agreed to the measures.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The November 2015 Paris attacks prompted a reevaluation of the German government's stance on EU migration policy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] While she did not directly limit the number of immigrants, Merkel tightened asylum policy in Germany, for example through more thorough vetting of migrants with respect to internal safety and security.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In August 2016, following the Würzburg train attack in Germany and various other Islamist terror attacks in Europe, Merkel's approval rating dropped to 47%.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Half of Germans did not want her to serve a fourth term in office, with only 42% in favour of another term in office.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In a poll from October that year, her approval rating was found to have risen again; 54% of Germans were found to be satisfied with the work of Merkel as Chancellor.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] According to another poll taken in November 2016, 59% were to found to be in favour of a renewed Chancellorship candidature in 2017.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] According to a poll carried out shortly after the 2016 Berlin truck attack, 56% of Germans named Merkel as a political leader they trusted to solve their country's problems.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In October 2016, Merkel travelled to Mali and Niger.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The diplomatic visit took place to discuss how their governments could improve conditions which caused people to flee those countries and how illegal migration through and from these countries could be reduced.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The migrant crisis spurred right-wing electoral preferences across Germany with the Alternative for Germany (AfD) gaining 12% of the vote in the 2017 German federal election.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] These developments prompted debates over the reasons for increased right-wing populism in Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Some researchers have argued that increased right-wing preferences are a result of the European migrant crisis, particularly the increasingly common perception that refugees constitute an ethnic and cultural threat to Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Some observers have described Merkel's policymaking with respect to the migrant crisis as a success.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2022, the United Nations' High Commissioner for Refugees granted Merkel the Nansen Award for her "courage and compassion" during the crisis.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, Merkel has also faced significant criticism, particularly with regards to her policymaking early in the crisis, which some critics describe as hypocritically unilateral.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2017 federal election, Merkel led her party to victory for the fourth time.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, both the CDU/CSU and the SPD received a significantly lower proportion of the vote than they did in 2013, and the CDU/CSU subsequently attempted to form a coalition with the FDP and Greens.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The SPD announced that they would go into the Opposition, both due to their loss of popular support and because the idea of another grand coalition was widely unpopular at the time.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The FDP eventually withdrew from negotiations with the CDU/CSU, leading to a stalemate.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The German President Frank-Walter Steinmeier subsequently appealed successfully to the SPD to change their hard stance against coalition with the CDU/CSU, and the SPD agreed to a third grand coalition with the CDU/CSU.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The negotiations leading up to this agreement were the longest in German post-war history, lasting almost six months.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] A YouGov survey published in late December 2017 found that just 36% of all respondents wanted Merkel to stay at the helm until 2021, while half of those surveyed voters called for a change at the top before the end of the legislature.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The Fourth Merkel cabinet was sworn in on 14 March 2018.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] As part of the newly formed government, the CSU's Horst Seehofer took over the role of Interior Minister.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Seehofer announced that he had a "master plan for faster asylum procedures, and more consistent deportations." Under Seehofer's plan, Germany would immediately reject prospective immigrants who had already been deported or were subject to an entry ban.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Additionally, the police would be instructed to turn away all applicants who had previously registered elsewhere in the EU, no matter if these countries agreed to take them back.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel feared that unilaterally sending migrants back to neighbouring countries without seeking a multilateral European agreement could endanger the stability of the European Union.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In June 2018, Seehofer issued an ultimatum to Merkel; as Interior Minister, he could unilaterally implement the policy without her support.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although he eventually agreed to cooperate with Merkel while she negotiated with other EU member countries, he went on to reject the EU agreement that she obtained.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 1 July 2018, during a meeting with party leadership, Seehofer declared his intention to resign from his position in protest.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] During the night of 2 July 2018, Seehofer and Merkel announced they had settled their differences and agreed to instead accept a compromise of tighter border control.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] As a result of the agreement, Seehofer agreed to not resign, and to negotiate bilateral agreements with the specific countries himself.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Seehofer received some criticism for his stance in the crisis.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the initial phases of the pandemic, Germany established a crisis team to manage Germany's containment policy and pandemic response.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In late February 2020, referring to this crisis team, Merkel recommended an approach characterised by moderation and an avoidance of extreme or universal measures (*Maß und Mitte*).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The speech was well-received both nationally and internationally, receiving widespread attention and an award for "speech of the year".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 6 April 2020, Merkel stated: "In my view ... the European Union is facing the biggest test since its foundation and member states must show greater solidarity so that the bloc can emerge stronger from the economic crisis unleashed by the pandemic".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has won international plaudits for her handling of the pandemic in Germany.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Later that month, Merkel was praised for her accessible explanation of the basic reproduction number, which had been an important metric in the German government's pandemic response.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel opposed mandatory vaccinations, instead stressing scientific literacy and education.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] During the German presidency of the European Council, Merkel spearheaded negotiations for the Next Generation EU reconstruction package.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 29 October 2018, Merkel announced that she would not seek reelection as leader of CDU at their party conference in December 2018, but intended to remain as chancellor until the 2021 German federal election was held.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She stated that she did not plan to seek any political office after this.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The resignations followed October setbacks for the CSU in the Bavarian state election and for the CDU in the Hessian state election.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In August 2019, Merkel hinted that she might return to academia at the end of her term in 2021.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She decided not to suggest any person as her successor as leader of the CDU.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, political observers had long considered Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer as Merkel's protégé groomed for succession.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] This view was confirmed when Kramp-Karrenbauer – widely seen as the chancellor's favourite for the post – was voted to succeed Merkel as leader of the CDU in December 2018.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Kramp-Karrenbauer's elevation to Defence Minister after Ursula von der Leyen's departure to become president of the European Commission also boosted her standing as Merkel's most likely candidate for succession.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2019, media outlets speculated that Kramp-Karrenbauer might take over Merkel's position as Chancellor sooner than planned if the current governing coalition proved unsustainable.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The possibility was neither confirmed nor denied by the party.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In February 2020, Kramp-Karrenbauer announced that she would resign as party leader of the CDU in the summer, after party members in Thuringia defied official party lines and voted with Alternative for Germany to support an FDP candidate for minister-president.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Kramp-Karrenbauer was succeeded by Armin Laschet at the 2021 CDU leadership election.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In the 2021 federal election, the SPD won the most votes.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] This necessitated long negotiations among the various parties to form a government.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 23 November 2021, a new coalition was announced, with Olaf Scholz nominated to succeed Merkel.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel continued to serve as chancellor until 8 December 2021, when Scholz was sworn in.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The constituency she had held since its establishment in the German reunification was won by Anna Kassautzki (SPD).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 31 January 2022, less than two months after she left office, her long-time rival Friedrich Merz, whom she beat in 2002 to become leader of the opposition, took over as leader of the CDU.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In April that year, a spokesperson for Merkel stated that she "stood by her position at the NATO summit in Bucharest in 2008", when she had opposed Ukraine's membership in the North Atlantic Alliance, a decision that had come under increased scrutiny.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 1 June 2022, Merkel made her first semi-public comments about political affairs since leaving office, at a retirement party for Reiner Hoffmann, the president of the German Trade Union Confederation.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 7 June 2022, Merkel made her first public comments.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She also said that by the end of her chancellorship in September 2021, it had been clear that Putin was moving in the direction of conflict and that he was finished with the Normandy Format talks.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Following her retirement, Merkel wrote a memoir called *Freedom* (Freiheit), with her longtime assistant and adviser, Beate Baumann.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] It was released on 26 November 2024 with the title *Freedom: Memories 1954–2021*.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The book was published in 30 languages and consists of 736 pages.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In January 2025, Merkel criticised Friedrich Merz for introducing a non-binding resolution supporting restrictions on immigration that passed in the Bundestag with the help of the AfD.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Following the CDU/CSU's victory in the 2025 German federal election, Merkel attended the first round of voting in the Bundestag to elect Merz as Chancellor on 6 May 2025.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In October 2025 Merkel gave a long interview to Hungarian media in which she made a number of controversial statements, partly reverting her previous position.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She said that in 2021 she attempted to build a "new diplomatic format" to speak to Putin "as EU", but this was "opposed by Poland and Baltic states" and then she left her position shortly before the war broke out in 2022, thus indirectly blaming the countries for the war.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She also said that "coronavirus pandemic that played a decisive role in Russia’s invasion of Ukraine" because Putin was afraid of the virus and didn't want to talk face to face.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Anyone who doesn't accept that is in the wrong place here." She continued to say that immigrants should integrate and adopt Germany's culture and values.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] This added to a growing debate within Germany on the acceptable levels and mechanisms of immigration, its effects on Germany, and the degree to which Muslim immigrants had integrated into German society.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel is in favour of a "mandatory solidarity mechanism" for relocation of asylum-seekers from Italy and Greece to other EU member states as part of the long-term solution to Europe's migrant crisis.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel's foreign policy has focused on strengthening European cooperation and international trade agreements.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She and her governments have been closely associated with the change through trade (*Wandel durch Handel*) policy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] For this, she has come under criticism, especially after the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has been widely described as the *de facto* leader of the European Union throughout her tenure as Chancellor.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2015, with the absence of Stephen Harper, Merkel became the only leader to have attended every G20 meeting since the first in 2008, having been present at a record fifteen summits as of 2021.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She hosted the twelfth meeting at the 2017 G20 Hamburg summit.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel favors the Association Agreement between Ukraine and the European Union.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In December 2012, she stated that its implementation depends on reforms in Ukraine.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel expressed support for Israel's right to self-defence in the context of the 2014 Israel–Gaza conflict.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She telephoned Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on 9 July to condemn "without reservation rocket fire on Israel".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] On 20 June 2018, which was World Refugee Day, Merkel said that there had been "no moral or political justification" for the post-war expulsion of ethnic Germans from Central and Eastern European countries.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] At the World Economic Forum in Davos, 2013, Merkel said that Europe had only 7% of the global population and produced only 25% of the global GDP, but that it accounted for almost 50% of global social expenditure.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] She went on to say that Europe could only maintain its prosperity by being innovative and measuring itself against the best.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] After this, the comparison became a central element in major speeches.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The *Financial Times* commented: "Although Ms Merkel stopped short of suggesting that a ceiling on social spending might be one yardstick for measuring competitiveness, she hinted as much in the light of soaring social spending in the face of an ageing population.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Merkel has been credited as a key part of 2007 G8 negotiations that led to a significantly more ambitious renewable energy transition commitment than had been anticipated.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2010, the coalition government published a long-term plan for sustainable development of the electrical grid until 2050; efforts to transition to sustainable and otherwise preferable sources of energy have been termed Energy Transition (*Energiewende*).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although the initial plan was criticised for lifetime extensions of nuclear power plants, it was amended following the Fukushima nuclear disaster, and the last nuclear power plants in Germany were shut down in April 2023.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The plan also aimed at a 40% reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 2020, a goal that was initially achieved largely due to reductions in demand during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] However, emissions increased to a level above the target in 2022.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In preparation for the 2015 Paris Climate Change Conference, Merkel announced that Germany would significantly increase its contributions to international climate aid and financing by 2020.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2016, some observers criticised Merkel's lack of action with regards to climate change that year.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2017, Merkel criticised the Trump administration's decision to withdraw from the 2015 Paris Agreement and reaffirmed the commitment of the remaining G20 members to the treaty.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In early 2019, a governmental commission appointed by the coalition government approved a plan to phase out coal power plants by 2038, allocating a budget of €40 billion to the plan.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In September 2019, the Merkel government announced a set of climate change mitigation policies with a total budget of €54 billion.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Although described as a "new beginning for Germany's climate policy" by then-minister of the environment Svenja Schulze, the package was widely criticised; environmental protection groups have labelled it insufficient, and opposition parties have argued that it is ineffective.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] Prominent climate scientists have called it "a failure of the political system" and "ridiculous".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2009, Merkel announced plans to take on additional government debt in order to stimulate economic growth, arguing that this should take priority over other fiscal concerns.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] The Merkel government's tax policy at the time was widely criticised, mostly for taking on additional debt instead of increasing tax rates at high levels of income.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2010, Merkel expressed support for a global financial transaction tax, but was ultimately unsuccessful in international negotiations on the matter.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p01] In 2019, Merkel argued for the importance of a balanced government budget, rejecting calls for additional investment to stimulate growth.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's chancellorship attracted criticism across several policy areas, including her handling of Islam and public integration debates, the eurozone crisis, migration, Turkey, China, Russia, energy policy and the wider development of Euroscepticism in Europe.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for attending the 2010 M100 Media Award ceremony at which Danish cartoonist Kurt Westergaard was honoured.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Westergaard had drawn cartoons central to the Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Although Merkel defended her attendance as a statement in favour of press freedom, critics argued that her presence gave political legitimacy to material widely viewed by Muslims as offensive.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The Central Council of Muslims in Germany criticised the decision, saying that Westergaard had insulted the Prophet Muhammad and that the award came at a highly charged time in Germany's debate over Islam and immigration.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Politicians from Die Linke and the Greens also criticised Merkel's participation, while commentators noted the sensitivity of a German chancellor and leader of the Christian Democratic Union personally honouring the cartoonist during a period of intense debate over Muslim integration.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised from within her own political camp after stating in 2015 that "Islam is part of Germany", a formulation previously associated with former German president Christian Wulff.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Volker Kauder, then parliamentary group leader of the CDU/CSU, rejected the statement, saying that Muslims belonged to Germany but Islam did not.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Several of Merkel's public formulations became targets of criticism and ridicule.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Her frequent use of the term *alternativlos* to describe measures taken during the European sovereign-debt crisis was criticised as politically undemocratic, since it implied that alternatives to her policies were unnecessary or illegitimate.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The term was named Germany's Un-word of the Year in 2010.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Her 2013 statement that the internet was *Neuland* also prompted widespread online mockery and criticism.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's handling of the European sovereign-debt crisis was one of the most criticised aspects of her chancellorship.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her government turned the eurozone crisis into a test of fiscal discipline and debtor-country compliance, rather than treating it as a structural crisis of the monetary union.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Commentators and politicians in several EU member states accused Berlin of imposing excessive austerity on countries such as Greece, Spain and Portugal, deepening social hardship and fuelling anti-EU sentiment.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel also faced criticism from within her own political tradition.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In July 2011, *Der Spiegel* reported that former chancellor Helmut Kohl, Merkel's former mentor and a central figure in German reunification and European integration, had criticised her handling of the eurozone crisis.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism intensified during the 2015 Greek bailout negotiations, after the election of the Syriza-led government in January 2015.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel and the German government were identified with the creditor side's insistence on prior reforms, fiscal consolidation, conditionality and privatisation before the release of further funds.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In July 2015, after Greece missed a repayment to the International Monetary Fund, its second bailout expired and Greek voters rejected the creditors' proposal in a referendum, Merkel and other eurozone leaders pressed Greece to accept a third bailout under stricter terms.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics accused Merkel and finance minister Wolfgang Schäuble of using the threat of *Grexit* as leverage and of forcing Greece to surrender fiscal and economic sovereignty in order to remain in the eurozone.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Criticism also focused on the requirement for Greece to privatise or transfer control of state assets.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents argued that the bailout framework went beyond fiscal adjustment by requiring the disposal of strategic Greek public assets, thereby weakening Greek economic sovereignty.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The 14 Greek regional airports concession became one of the most symbolic examples.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] A preliminary deal with a consortium led by Germany's Fraport AG had been agreed in 2014, but was reviewed after the Syriza government came to power.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In August 2015, shortly after the third bailout agreement, Greece confirmed that it would proceed with the concession as part of the latest bailout with its lenders.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The agreement was signed in December 2015 and Fraport Greece began operating the airports in April 2017 under a long-term concession.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] For critics in Greece and southern Europe, the Fraport concession became emblematic of a wider creditor-driven programme in which public assets were transferred to foreign operators while Greek society absorbed the costs of austerity.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The same criticism was applied to other privatisations, including the sale of a majority stake in the Port of Piraeus to China's COSCO, the sale of railway operator TRAINOSE to Italy's Ferrovie dello Stato Italiane and the sale of a further stake in OTE to Germany's Deutsche Telekom.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Scholars and commentators have linked the eurozone crisis and the subsequent austerity policies to the rise of Euroscepticism and radical parties across Europe.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In this criticism, Merkel's crisis management is presented not only as an economic policy failure, but also as a political factor that weakened trust in EU institutions and mainstream parties in several member states.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's response to the European migrant crisis of 2015 was heavily criticised by opponents in Germany and abroad.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that the size and speed of the inflow exposed weaknesses in Germany's administrative capacity and contributed to a public backlash against Merkel's government.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Analysts have linked this backlash to the rise of the Alternative for Germany and to broader changes in the German party system.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's refugee policy also became a recurring target in far-right and Eurosceptic discourse, where it was portrayed as evidence of elite detachment from public concerns over borders, identity and security.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] More broadly, the eurozone crisis and the refugee crisis have been identified in academic literature as key drivers of rising Euroscepticism and support for radical parties across Europe in the 2010s.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics of Merkel argue that her role in both crises made her one of the central political figures associated with this wider backlash.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for her pragmatic relationship with Turkish president Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, particularly after the 2015 refugee crisis.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her reliance on Turkey to reduce irregular migration into the European Union gave Erdoğan political leverage over Germany and the EU at a time when his government was facing increasing criticism over human rights, press freedom and the rule of law.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents argued that the arrangement prioritised border control over refugee protection and made the EU dependent on cooperation with an increasingly authoritarian Turkish government.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel faced further criticism during the Böhmermann affair in April 2016, when her government allowed prosecutors to consider a case against German comedian Jan Böhmermann after Erdoğan complained about a satirical poem.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics accused Merkel of failing to defend freedom of expression and of accommodating Erdoğan.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] A Reuters-reported poll found that two thirds of Germans opposed her decision to allow the prosecution to proceed.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised over Germany's approach to Turkish pressure on Greece and Cyprus.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] During the 2020 Greek–Turkish border crisis, Erdoğan opened Turkey's border with Europe and thousands of migrants attempted to enter Greece.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel criticised Erdoğan for using refugees to express political grievances with the EU, but critics argued that Germany's wider policy remained constrained by its dependence on Turkish cooperation.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Similar criticism arose during the Eastern Mediterranean crisis, when Turkey carried out energy exploration and maritime claims disputed by Greece and Cyprus.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that Germany under Merkel prioritised mediation and de-escalation over firm solidarity with Greece and Cyprus.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Academic analysis of the crisis noted that Germany avoided full identification with the positions of Cyprus and Greece, objected to a sanctions-based agenda against Turkey and sought to maintain open diplomatic channels with Ankara.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised for failing to take a tougher line towards the People's Republic of China.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that her governments prioritised German commercial interests and export access over stronger public criticism of Beijing on human rights, Hong Kong and strategic dependency.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Her approach was frequently characterised by opponents as overly cautious and too focused on trade.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism intensified during the Hong Kong protests and wider European debates over relations with China.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's China policy was criticised as an example of Germany's reluctance to confront authoritarian governments when major economic interests were involved.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Some commentators later described China as one of the major weaknesses of her foreign-policy legacy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Merkel faced renewed criticism over her Russia policy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that she had underestimated Vladimir Putin's ambitions, relied too heavily on diplomacy and détente, and failed to prepare Germany and Europe for a more confrontational Russian policy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Her governments were criticised for allowing Germany to become heavily dependent on Russian energy, including through Nord Stream 1 and Nord Stream 2.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was also criticised over the condition of the Bundeswehr during and after her chancellorship.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that Germany's armed forces had been neglected, underfunded and left poorly prepared despite growing security risks in Europe.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] This criticism became more prominent after the invasion of Ukraine, when Germany's defence policy came under closer domestic and international scrutiny.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's broader approach to Russia was associated with *Wandel durch Handel*, the policy of pursuing close economic ties with authoritarian governments in the expectation that trade would encourage moderation or democratisation.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] After Russia's invasion of Ukraine, this policy came under intense criticism, with Merkel receiving much of the blame for Germany's strategic dependency on Moscow.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelenskyy also criticised Merkel and former French president Nicolas Sarkozy for blocking Ukraine's NATO aspirations in 2008.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel defended the decision, arguing that Ukraine would have been militarily weaker had the conflict escalated earlier.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel's energy policy was criticised for combining the phase-out of nuclear power with continued dependence on fossil fuel imports, including Russian gas.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics argued that the nuclear phase-out reduced reliable domestic low-carbon power generation and increased Germany's exposure to imported energy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The criticism became stronger during the 2021–2022 global energy crisis, when rising energy prices and supply concerns placed Germany's energy strategy under scrutiny.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Opponents also criticised the interaction between Germany's nuclear exit, coal phase-out and climate policy.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] While Merkel's governments supported the European Green Deal and long-term decarbonisation, critics argued that the transition was poorly sequenced and left Germany vulnerable to both energy insecurity and high prices.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was criticised in debates over the wider direction of the European Union.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Some politicians and commentators argued that German-led austerity during the eurozone crisis, the handling of the migration crisis and the reluctance of EU leaders to accommodate British concerns contributed to anti-EU sentiment.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In debates over Brexit, critics claimed that continental Europe, including Germany under Merkel, bore part of the responsibility for the political climate that led to the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] This argument was particularly common among Eurosceptic and right-wing critics, who linked the eurozone and migration crises to declining trust in EU institutions.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Studies of far-right discourse in Germany have noted that AfD politicians sometimes portrayed Merkel's refugee policy as contributing to Brexit.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Scholars generally treat Brexit as the result of multiple domestic and European factors, but critics of Merkel have continued to cite it as part of a broader backlash against the EU during her period of leadership.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was widely described as the *de facto* leader of the European Union throughout her tenure as Chancellor.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] She was named the world's second most powerful person by *Forbes* magazine in 2012 and 2015, following Barack Obama and Vladimir Putin respectively, the highest ranking ever achieved by a woman.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] On 26 March 2014, Merkel became the longest-serving incumbent head of government in the European Union.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In December 2015, Merkel was named as *Time* magazine's Person of the Year, with the magazine's cover declaring her to be the "Chancellor of the Free World".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In 2018, Merkel was named the most powerful woman in the world for a record fourteenth time by *Forbes*.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Following the election of Donald Trump to the US presidency in 2016, Merkel was described by *The New York Times* as "the Liberal West's Last Defender", and as the "leader of the free world" by a number of commentators, including Hillary Clinton.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In a 2018 survey, Merkel was found to be the most widely respected world leader.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] *The Atlantic* described her in 2019 as "the world's most successful living politician, on the basis of both achievement and longevity".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Harvard University President Larry Bacow described her as "one of the most widely admired and broadly influential statespeople of our time".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Critics have argued that Merkel's policymaking during the 2015 migrant crisis has damaged the integrity of the EU.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Some have also commented that Germany's failure to meet financial commitments to NATO, Merkel's blocking of the accession of Ukraine to NATO in 2008, and the abolishment of conscription have together weakened the positions of Germany and Europe following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has been described as having significantly shaped the political landscape of Germany, particularly the perceptions of those who grew up during her chancellorship; this demographic group has been referred to *Merkelkinder* (transl. children of Merkel).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] As a woman who is a politician from a centre-right party and also a scientist, Merkel has been compared by many in the English-language press to 20th-century British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Thatcher also had a science degree from Oxford University in chemistry.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Some have referred to her as "Iron Lady", "Iron Girl", and even "The Iron Frau", all alluding to Thatcher, whose nickname was "The Iron Lady".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Political commentators have debated the precise extent to which their agendas are similar.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Later in her tenure, Merkel acquired the nickname *"Mutti"* (a German familiar form of "mother").
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] She has also been called the "Iron Chancellor", in reference to Otto von Bismarck.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In 1977, at the age of 23, Merkel, then Angela Kasner, married physics student Ulrich Merkel (born 1953) and took his surname.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Her second and current husband is quantum chemist and professor Joachim Sauer, who has largely avoided media attention during and after Merkel's political career.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] They first met in 1981 and married in 1998.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has no children, but Sauer has two adult sons from a previous marriage.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Having grown up in East Germany, Merkel learned Russian at school.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] She was able to speak informally to Vladimir Putin in Russian but conducted diplomatic dialogue through an interpreter.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] She rarely spoke English in public, but delivered a small section of an address to the British Parliament in English in 2014.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel is a fervent football fan and was known to listen to games while in the Bundestag and to attend games of the national team in her official capacity, including Germany's 1–0 victory against Argentina in the 2014 World Cup Final.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has stated that her favorite film is *The Legend of Paul and Paula*, an East German movie released in 1973.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel has a fear of dogs, which developed after she was attacked by one in 1995.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Vladimir Putin brought in his Labrador Retriever during a press conference in 2007.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Putin claims he did not mean to scare her, though Merkel later observed, "I understand why he has to do this – to prove he's a man. ...
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Since 2017, Merkel has occasionally been seen shaking visibly on several public occasions, recovering shortly afterwards.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] After one such occasion, she attributed the shaking to dehydration, saying that she felt better after a drink of water.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In September 2021, after evading the question for most of her career, Merkel said that she considered herself a feminist.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The statement came in a conference along with Nigerian writer and feminist Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Since her retirement, Merkel has commented on the Russo-Ukrainian war, but has otherwise limited her involvement in political matters.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] She has instead focused on travelling, attending only "feel-good events" (*Wohlfühltermine*) in a private capacity.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] President Donald Trump, according to *Politico*, citing a forthcoming book by Jonathan Karl.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] The EKBO is a member of the Union of Protestant Churches in the EKD.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Before the 2004 merger of the Evangelical Church in Berlin-Brandenburg and the Evangelical Church in Silesian Upper Lusatia, Merkel belonged to the former.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In 2012, Merkel said, regarding her faith: "I am a member of the Protestant Church.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] I believe in God and religion is also my constant companion, and has been for the whole of my life.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] We as Christians should above all not be afraid of standing up for our beliefs." She also publicly declared that Germany suffers not from "too much Islam" but "too little Christianity".
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Since 1991, Merkel has sat annually for sitting and standing portraits by, and interview with, Herlinde Koelbl.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel was portrayed by Swiss actress Anna Katarina in the 2012 political satire film *The Dictator*.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] Merkel features as a main character in two of the three plays that make up the Europeans Trilogy (*Bruges*, *Antwerp*, and *Tervuren*) by Paris-based UK playwright Nick Awde: *Bruges* (2014) and *Tervuren* (2016).
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] A character named Merkel, accompanied by a sidekick called Schäuble, also appears as the sinister female henchman in Michael Paraskos's novel *In Search of Sixpence*.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] On the American sketch-comedy series *Saturday Night Live*, Merkel has been parodied by Kate McKinnon.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] On the British sketch-comedy *Tracey Ullman's Show*, comedian Tracey Ullman has parodied Merkel to international acclaim.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In 2016, a documentary film *Angela Merkel – The Unexpected* was produced by Broadview TV and MDR in collaboration with Arte and Das Erste.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] In 2024, a German TV show called 'Miss Merkel' reimagined her as a detective.
[src:angela-merkel/angela-merkel-p02] It is based on the bestselling novels by German writer David Safier and is a comedy that was a hit in Germany and then shown on public broadcaster RAI, dubbed into Italian.
